The objective of First Person Blackjack is to obtain a higher score than
the virtual dealer,without exceeding 21 points. The best hand is
Blackjack- when...the sum of the first two cards dealt is exactly 21.

●Played with 8 decks of cards.
●The cards are shuffled before each game.
●The-house always has 17 points.
●Double the bet on any first two cards.
●Divide the first cards with equal points.
●Only one division per hand.
●One card is dealt for each Split Ace.
●Do not fold after dividing.
●Insurance bets can only be made when the ●dealer has an Ace.
●Blackjack pays 3:2.
●Insurance pays 2:1.
●A game is considered a draw when the cards drawn are equal.

The game is played with 8 standard decks of 52 cards. The card values
are as follows:

●Cards 2 through 10 are counted at their face value.
●Face cards (, Q and K) are worth 10 each.
●Aces are worth 1 or 11, whichever is more advantageous.
  Note that a weak hand containing an Ace is worth 11.

There are five hands remaining. You can bet on one or more hands.
After placing your bet,click/tap the "DEAL Now" button to start dealing
the cards. Dealing starts with the hand closest to the box,continues
clockwise to the next player, and ends with the virtual dealer. One
face-up card is dealt to each hand and to the virtual dealer. Then, a
second face-up card must be dealt to each hand and the last face-up
card is dealt to the virtual dealer. The score for each hand is displayed
first next to the cards in each hand.

If the score of your first two cards is exactly 21,you
have Blackjack!

If the virtual dealer's upcard is an Ace, you have the option to purchase
insurance to cover the risk that the virtual dealer has a blackjack,even
if you also have a blackjack. The insurance bet is half of your main bet
and is calculated separately from the bet on your hand. The virtual
dealer's downcard counts toward blackjack. If there is no blackjack, the
round continues.If the virtual dealer has a blackjack but you do not, the
virtual dealer's hand wins. If both you and the dealer have blackjack, the
game ends in a tie and you receive a refund of your bet. Please note
that when the virtual dealer's upcard is a 10 or a face card, you do not
have the option to purchase insurance, and the virtual dealer's downcard
does not count toward blackjack.

When the virtual dealer does not have Blackjack when checking the first
two cards, it is the players' turn to increase the score of their hands by
choosing to deal additional cards.

If your starting hand score is not 21, you may decide to Double Down.
In this case, you will double your bet and receive only one more card in
your hand.Alternatively,youmay choose to Hit to receive an additional
card and increase your hand score. You may Hit more than once to
receive additional cards before deciding to Stand when you are satisfied
with your hand score.

If your starting hand is a pair of cards of the same rank, you may decide
to split the pair to have two separate hands, each with its own bet equal
to the main bet. After the second card has been dealt to both hands, you
can increase the score of these two hands by deciding to hit for more
cards. Alternatively, you may choose to stand when you are satisfied with
the score of your two hands. However, if you split your starting pair of
Aces, you will only receive one more card for each hand, without the
option to hit for more cards.

If the total points in your hand exceed 21, you bust and lose your bet
on that hand.

When deciding on all hands, the virtual dealer's face-down card is
revealed. The virtual dealer must draw a hand with less than 16 points
and must use a soft hand of 17 points or more. Note that the "soft hand"
includes an Ace, which is worth 11.

You win when your final hand is closer to 21 than the dealer's hand or
when the dealer busts. If the hands tie, the round ends in a tie and you
get your bet back.

If you decide to withdraw, you will receive the amount shown on the
Withdraw decision button when you make that decision.

Blackjack can only use two cards in the initial two-card deal. A split 21 is
not considered Blackjack. Therefore, a Blackjack beats a split 21.

A 21+3 side bet gives you the chance to win if your first two cards plus
the dealer's upcard have any of the following winning pairs (similar to
playing cards), each with a different bet

● Combined sequence - three of a kind, for example,3 Queens of Clubs.
●Straight Flush -in numerical sequence and same suit, for example:
10, Jand Q of DIAMONDS.
●Three of a Kind - same score but different suits, for example,
any 3-Kings of different suits.
●Straight-in arithmetic sequence, but with different sets, for example:
2 of Swords + 3 of Clubs + 4 of Hearts.
●Flush - a card that is not in sequence, for example: a 2, a 6 and a 10 of
Clubs.

This First Person Blackjack game includes optional side bets- Perfect
Pair and 21 +3.Please note that the main bet is required to place a side
bet. You have a chance to win on any side bet, regardless of whether or
not you win on the main bet later.

Perfect Pairs Side Bet: The Perfect Pairs side bet gives you the chance to
win if your first two cards consist of any pair for example, two Queens,
two Aces, or two 3s. There are three types of pairs, each with a different
bet:

● Double Bet -same sequence, for example two are Ace of Spades.
● Pair color bet- other suits of the same color, for example,
2 diamonds + 2 hearts.
● Pair Betting Combine different suits with different colors, for example,
10 Cards + 10 Clubs.

● Blackjack pays 3:2.
● The winning hand pays 1:1
● Insurance pays 2:1.
● Cash Out is usually paid at O.5 times the stake.

Perfect Double Bet     25:1
Double color bet         12:1
Pair combination bet    6:1

Synchronous Range  100:1
Straight Flush              40:1
Three of a kind            30:1
Hall                              10:1
Bin                                 5:1
